The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, December 26, 2003  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Dec. 25: Hughes Software Systems will double the business process outsourcing (BPO) divisions current manpower strength of 300 in 2004. The company is eyeing a revenue contribution of about 6 per cent from this division.																								y president and managing director Arun Kumar said the division is currently contributing about 1 per cent to the revenue.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 25: Punjab National Bank (PNB) plans to raise about Rs 400 crore through bonds issue this fiscal and another Rs 1,000 crore from overseas markets after getting permission from the government. The bank will soon seek Sebis approval for the Tier-II bonds issue, PNB chairman S. S. Kohli said.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 25: Justice Y. V. Chandrachud Committee that went into the mismanagement of Nedungadi Bank, has held the then chairman of the bank, R. K. Banthia, responsible but gave a clean chit to the Reserve Bank in dealing with the issue.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 25: The finance ministry has favoured slashing of statutory minimum cane price to Rs 64.5 per quintal, arguing that any major hike will result in bail-out packages. The government is yet to fix the smp due to inter-ministerial differences, official sources said.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 25: Reliance Industries (RIL) Jamnagar refinery output jumped 36.8 per cent to 2.69 million tonnes in November against 1.96 million tonnes of refined petroleum products produced in the same month last year. Jamnagar refinery operated at 121.6 per cent of its prorated installed capacity of 2.213 million tonnes per month to produce 2.692 million tonnes of refined production.																								 Mumbai, Dec. 25: The Centre will improve coordination among various ministries and upgrade the infrastructure facilities at various ports to give a thrust to cruise shipping, Union shipping minister Shatrughan Sinha said. 																								 Mumbai, Dec. 25: Pure gold (99.9 purity) prices have reached an all-time high of Rs 6,190 due to persistent demand from stockists along with good buying ahead of new year. In the world markets, rise in gold prices was mainly due to fall in dollar against the euro, dealers said. Ready silver (.999 fineness) closed at Rs 9,295 on the bullion market.
